            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.17.16"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">16</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">OFFICE OF THE
                        REGISTER OF COPYRIGHTS
                
                HAH:MPF
                6-30-37
                
                LIBRARY OF CONGRESS
                COPYRIGHT OFFICE
                    <lb/>
                WASHINGTON
                </fw>
                
                Attention: Mr. John G. Neihardt
                
                JUL-1 1937
                
                    <salute>Gentlemen:</salute> 
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to your letter of June 25 relative to a novel copyrighted by a publisher in 1912 under contract with the author but without stipulation therein as to moving picture rights. You ask whether the latter rights belong to the author now? That would seem to depend upon the correct interpretation of the original contract. If the author merely conveyed what is commonly known as the "book rights," then it is conceivable that <del>the</del> court might hold that he meant to reserve to himself the other rights, such as the right of serialization and dramatization. The making of a motion picture based upon the story would, according to the Supreme Court of the United States in the "Ben Hur" case decided in 1911, be a dramatization thereof. If on the other hand it was the intention of the author to dispose of the entire right to the publisher without restriction, limitation or qualification, the conclusion would seem to be,by copyrighting the novel in  his own name the publisher acquired under the contract all the rights granted by law,including the right of dramatization.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Respectfully,</salute>
                    <signed>C.L. Bouv&#233;</signed>
                    <signed>C.L. Bouv&#233;
                    Register of Copyrights.</signed>
                
                St. Louis Post-Dispatch
                Editorial Department
                St. Louis, Missouri.
                
            </div1>
